%N A390512 The all-integers indexing of lexicographically ordered 01 words; a bijection from the positive integers to the integers.
%C A390512 Each binary word w having first letter 1 is identical (with letters as digits) to the binary representation of n; e.g., a(6) = 3 is the all-integers index of w = 11, and 11 is the binary representation of 3. The positions of words with first letter 1 form a dispersion as in A345254. The positions of the words having first letter 0 form a dispersion as in A390513.
%F A390512 a(n) = 1 - 2^(x-1) - k if k < 2^(x - 1), and a(n) = k if k >= 2^(x - 1), where x=floor(log_2(n + 1)) and x = n + 1 - 2^x.
%e A390512 In the following list, w(n) = n-th binary word in the lexicographic ordering.
%e A390512    n     w(n)    a(n)
%e A390512    1       0       0
%e A390512    2       1       1
%e A390512    3      00      -1
%e A390512    4      01      -2
%e A390512    5      10       2
%e A390512    6      11       3
%e A390512    7     000      -3
%e A390512    8     001      -4
%e A390512    9     010      -5
%e A390512   10     011      -6
%e A390512   11     100       4
%e A390512   12     101       5
%t A390512 a[n_] := Module[{x, s, k, h}, x = Floor[Log[2, n + 1]];
%t A390512 s = 2^x - 1; k = n - s; h = 2^(x - 1); If[k < h, 1 - h - k, k ]]
%t A390512 t = Table[a[n], {n, 1, 100}]
%t A390512 TableForm[Transpose[{Range[100], t}], TableHeadings -> {None, {"n", "a(n)"}}]
